data.reasoningText:
The issue is that in the test `Create_POST_InvalidModelState_ReturnsView`, the `Instructor` object has `CourseAssignments = null`, so when `PopulateAssignedCourseData` is called after model state validation fails, it tries to `instructor.CourseAssignments.Select(...)` which fails on null.

Looking at the `InstructorsController.Create` POST action:
```csharp
if (selectedCourses != null)
{
    instructor.CourseAssignments = new List<CourseAssignment>();
    ...
}
if (ModelState.IsValid)


```

When `ModelState.IsValid` is false AND `selectedCourses` is null, the instructor's `CourseAssignments` won't be initialized. So `PopulateAssignedCourseData` gets a null `CourseAssignments`. The method then tries to create a HashSet from `instructor.CourseAssignments.Select(...)`, which throws a null reference exception since `CourseAssignments` was never initialized.

The test needs to ensure the instructor has an initialized `CourseAssignments` collection before calling the method, just like the production code expects.

```

